==Welsh, English, French, Celtic Mythology==
===Etymology===
From the Celtic name Drystan

Derived from drest meaning "riot" or "tumult". 

===Pronounced===
TRIS-tan (English), trees-TAWN (French)

===Namesakes===
In [[Celtic]] [[legend]] a [[knight]] named Tristan was sent to [[Ireland]] in order to fetch Isolde, who was to be the bride of [[King Mark]] of [[Cornwall]]. Instead, Tristan and Isolde end up falling in love.

